            <abstract>
                <p>This keyword is used to classify genres of texts appearing in the manuscripts (for the types of additiones, a specific keyword <ref type="authFile"
                    corresp="PoemQene"
                    >PoemQene</ref> is additionally used.</p>
                <p>Despite the wide-spread opinion that qǝne is a poetic improvisation which is not written down, manuscripts contain unexpectedly many of them in additional notes or in collections of qǝne-poems. 
                    Frequently it is clearly stated the poem is qǝne, and the type and the author are indicated.</p>
                <p>Wherever possible, we define qǝne-forms according to the classification of 
                    <bibl><ptr target="bm:Guidi1900Qene"/><citedRange unit="page">4-5</citedRange></bibl> and mark them with specific keywords.
                    Cf. 
                    <ref type="authFile" corresp="GubaeQana"/> (2 verses),
                    <ref type="authFile" corresp="EtanaMogar"/> (2, 7 or 11 verses),  
                    <ref type="authFile" corresp="Mibazhu"/> (3 verses),                    
                    <ref type="authFile" corresp="Wazema"/> (5 verses),
                    <ref type="authFile" corresp="Zayeeze"/> (5 verses),
                    <ref type="authFile" corresp="Sellase"/> (6 verses),
                    <ref type="authFile" corresp="Mawaddes"/> (8 verses),
                    <ref type="authFile" corresp="Kwellekomu"/> (9 verses),              
                    <ref type="authFile" corresp="KebrYeeti"/> (3 verses).
                    When it is indicated, we also specify the mode, i.e.:
                    <ref type="authFile" corresp="ArarayMode"/> (joyous),
                    <ref type="authFile" corresp="EzelMode"/> (solemn),
                    <ref type="authFile" corresp="GeezMode"/> (solemn).
                </p>
